03787nam a22005175i 9780773569218DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20012001xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735692187 a10.1515/97807735692182doi  a(DE-B1597)655673  a(OCoLC)741349811  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aBX8252.P7 ǂb E446 2001eb 7aREL0440002bisacsh04a306.6/87/097121 aEmery, George, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMethodist Church on the Prairies, 1896-1914 /cGeorge Emery. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2001] 4c©2001  a1 online resource (296 p.) :billus., figures  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMcGill-Queen's Studies in the History of Religion ;v4100tFront Matter -- tContents -- tTables -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tThe Prairie West as a Methodist Challenge -- tThe Methodist Polity and the Social Profile of the Church -- tMethodist Traditions -- tMoney -- tClergy -- tLaity -- tMethodists and Non-Anglo-Saxon Immigrants -- tAll People’s Mission, Winnipeg -- tThe Ukrainian Missions in Alberta -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Methodist Church met the challenge with a centralized polity and a cross-class, gender-variegated, evolving religious culture. It relied on wealthy laymen to raise special funds, while small gifts fed its regular funds. Young bachelors from Ontario and Britain filled the pastorate, although low pay, inexperience, and poor supervision caused many to quit. Membership growth was slow due to low population density and church-resistant elements in the Methodist population (bachelors, immigrant co-religionists, and transients), and missions to non-Anglo-Saxon immigrants in Winnipeg, Edmonton, and rural Alberta spread Methodist values but gained few members. In The Methodist Church on the Prairies, 1896-1914, the first scholarly study of church history in the prairie region, George Emery uses quantitative methods and social interpretation to show that the Methodist Church was a cross-class institution with a dynamic evangelical culture, not a middle-class institution whose culture was undergoing secularization. He demonstrates that the Methodist's achievement on the prairies was impressive and compared favourably with what Presbyterians and Anglicans achieved.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aRELIGION / Christianity / Methodist.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077356921840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773569218423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773569218/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles